            <div class="story-promo__info" dir="auto">
                <strong class="story-promo__hed">North Carolina Supreme Court Secretly Squashed Discipline of Two GOP Judges Who Admitted to Violating Judicial Code</strong>
                            </div>
        </a>

    
</aside>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="87.0">The Brennan Center for Justice at NYU School of Law <a href="https://www.brennancenter.org/sites/default/files/publications/Judicial_Recusal_Reform.pdf">proposed a series of reforms in 2016</a>, including independent review of all motions for disqualification — at both the U.S. and state supreme courts — so judges don’t effectively serve as the final arbiters of their own biases. Brennan also advocated ending the common practice of judges keeping their reasons for recusal — or non-recusal — secret, which can stymie the appeals process and create a void in case law.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="88.0">Critics have argued the reforms could slow the wheels of justice and allow political actors to weaponize recusal. Many advocates for reform see transparency measures as an achievable next step.</p>

<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="88.1">“The fix is really hard,” said Amanda Frost, professor of law at the University of Virginia. But “transparency would improve the process for everyone.”</p>
        
    
                    
    
    
